@8thMountain sure, renting is throwing money away. Buying is investing in something which has value which tends to become more valuable. That's the long and short of it. If rent is 1k a month, and you rent for 10 years, that's 120k that's you've spent on housing that you will never see again. Whereas if you spent that on a house you have equity in it. And even if you have to move you can sell/rent out your purchased house for profit. 

Yes there may be times where you won't be able to move on a whim because you own a house and you have to sell it first. But if you settle down and get a job that pays even remotely decently then purchase a house within a reasonable time, you eventually won't have to pay rent or housing payments. Which is imperative, along with investing money, for retirement. 

Are there corner case situations where one may get a short stick by purchasing a house? Sure, but there are far more people who would simply benefit from it. As a general rule is far better to purchase a house rather then rent.

